        "text": "ἀσφαλές τι γράψαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Dig.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xlix., 6. “Post appellationem interpositam litteræ dandæ sunt ab eo, a quo appellatum est, ad eum qui de appellatione cogniturus est, sive principem, sive quem alium, quas litt. dimissorias sive Apostolos appellant” (Wetstein and Blass).—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τῷ κυρίῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": title refused by Augustus and Tiberius because it savoured too much of the relationship between a master and a slave, and perhaps because it seemed a title more fitting to God (as Wetstein explains it), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Suet., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Aug",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[397], 53, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Tiber.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 27, and Tacitus, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ann.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ii., 87. It was accepted by Caligula and succeeding emperors (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Pliny’s Letter to Trajan with the frequent ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Dominus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), although Alexander Severus forbade it to be applied to him; for other instances, and instances on inscriptions, see Wetstein, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Deissmann, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Neue Bibelstudien",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 44, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Bibelstudien",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 77, 78, and Tert[398], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Apol.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 34, Polyc., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Martyr.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", viii., 2, ix. 2, who refused to utter it with reference to Cæsar. For the due significance of the word in St. Luke, who uses it more frequently of Christ than the other Evangelists, see especially Wetstein, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀνακρίσεως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": here not in its strictly legal and judicial sense of a preliminary inquiry, but an inquiry into the case, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with a view to sending a report to the emperor as judge, Renan, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Saint Paul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", p. 544, and Zöckler, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Festus knew what the charges were, but not their significance, and he hoped to obtain some definite information from Agrippa or Paul—he wanted something ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀσφαλές",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Paul had contradicted the charge of treason, and what was left, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", seemed full of obscurity and absurdity.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[397] Augustine.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[398]ert. Tertullian.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unto my lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Octavianus by an edict forbade the title “Lord” to be given to him. The practice had its rise from parasites. But you find “Dominus” often used in Pliny’s letters to Trajan. So that not many emperors were like Octavian.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "before you",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Spoken with a glance towards the chief priests and great persons who were present on the bench.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "specially before thee",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i.e. as one most likely to be able to clear up the difficulties which I feel about the prisoner.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 25:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Τῷ κυρίῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to my lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Cæsar. Lately this, appellation, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Lord",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", had arisen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 26.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "- King",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for O ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "king",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V.; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "may",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "might",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", A.V. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "My lord",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "cmt_word",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "My lord",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "τῷ κυτίῳ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Suetonius tells us ('Life of Augustus,' 53) that Augustus abhorred the title of \"lord,\" and looked upon it as a curse and an insult when applied to himself. Tiberius also ('Life of Tiberius,' 27), being once called \"lord\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "dominus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") by some one, indignantly repudiated the title. But it was frequently applied to Trajan by Pithy, and the later emperors seem to have accepted it. It was likely to grow up first in the East. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Examination",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀνακρίσεως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", here only in the New Testament; but it is found in 3Macc. 7:4 in the same sense as here, viz. of a judicial examination (the complaint being that Jews were put to death  ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἄνευ πάσης ἀνακρίσεως καὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐξετάσεως",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); specially the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "precious examination",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the prisoner made for the information of the judge who was to try the case. At Athens the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀνάκρισις",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was a preliminary examination held to decide whether an action at law should be allowed. The verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀνακρίνω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to examine, occurs six times in the Gospel of St. Luke and the Acts (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 23:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 4:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 12:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.), and ten times in St. Paul's Epistles (see also Hist. of Susanna 48). Acts 25:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lord (κυρίῳ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "An instance of Luke's accuracy. The title \"lord\" was refused by the first two emperors, Augustus and Tiberius. The emperors who followed accepted it. In the time of Domitian it was a recognized title. Antoninus Pius was the first who put it on his coins. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]